TypeScript is a programming language that is a superset of JavaScript. It is designed to add static typing to JavaScript, which helps to catch errors at compile time and improve code readability. TypeScript was created by Microsoft and is now an open-source project.

Duck typing is a programming concept that allows a function or method to be called on an object without checking if the object has the necessary properties or methods. The idea is that if an object "quacks" like a duck, it can be treated as a duck. In other words, an object can be used in a particular way as long as it behaves like the expected type.

In TypeScript, duck typing can be achieved by using generic types and type inference. For example, you can define a function that takes an object of any type and calls a method on it without checking if the method exists. This allows you to use any object that has the necessary method without explicitly specifying its type.

Here's an example:

```
function doSomething(obj: any) {
  obj.quack();
}

let duck: Duck = new Duck();
doSomething(duck); // This will work because duck has a quack method

class Duck {
  quack() {
    console.log("Quack!");
  }
}
```

In this example, we define a function called doSomething() that takes an object of any type (any). We then create a class called Duck that has a quack() method. Finally, we create an instance of Duck and pass it to the doSomething() function. Because Duck has a quack() method, the function will work even though we haven't explicitly specified the type of obj.

This is just one example of how duck typing can be achieved in TypeScript. There are many other ways to use duck typing in TypeScript, depending on your specific needs.

